Instead, the Peace Treaty between Italy and the Allied Powers established the new borders. This treaty resulted in the annexation of some Slovene territories, such as Inner Carniola, Styria, and Lower Carniola, but it also freed other territories, such as Eastern Friuli, Gorizia, and Gradisca. On the other hand, the Peace Treaty of Rapallo of 1920 gave Slovenia the overall border. Because of the Peace Settlement of Paris of 1919, Slovenia became a part of the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes, where all decisions were made by the majority.1
Slovenian identity, therefore, needed to be re-developed.
